Strings in Java
String: Object creation and main methods

Object Creation:
Using new keyword: String str = new String("Hello");
Using string literal: String str = "Hello";
Main Methods:
length()
charAt(int index)
substring(int beginIndex, int endIndex)
contains(CharSequence s)
equals(Object anObject)
isEmpty()
toUpperCase(), toLowerCase()
trim()
replace(CharSequence target, CharSequence replacement)
String comparison and String Pool

String comparison:
Using equals(): str1.equals(str2)
Using == operator (compares reference, not value): str1 == str2
String Pool:
Strings in Java stored in a special memory area called the String Pool.  If the string already exists, the reference to the pooled instance is returned and a new string is added to the pool.

Escape Sequences in Java
\n - Newline
\t - Tab
\\ - Backslash
\" - Double quote
\' - Single quote
String Formatting
Use String.format()
Example: String.format("%.2f", Math.PI) to format to 2 decimal places.
Regular Expressions in Java
Use Pattern and Matcher classes.
Example: To check if a string contains only digits: Pattern.matches("\\d+", str)
